The '''rufous-bellied kookaburra''' ('''''Dacelo gaudichaud'''''), originally known as '''Gaudichaud's kookaburra''' after French botanist [[Charles Gaudichaud-Beaupré]], is a species of [[kookaburra]] that is widely distributed through the forests of lowland [[New Guinea]].

It has a black cap, blue-tinged wings, and a pale, rufous belly and tail feathers, but its white bill distinguishes it very clearly from other kookaburras with their black bills. Juveniles, however, have a dark-grey bill.<ref name="kingfishers">{{cite book| author = C. Hilary Fry|author2=Kathie Fry | title = Kingfishers, Bee-Eaters, & Rollers: A Handbook| date = 2000-01-01| isbn = 978-0-691-04879-6| pages = 128–129 }}</ref> Like the [[blue-winged kookaburra]], the sexes can be distinguished by the colour of the tail feathers, blue in males and rufous in females and immature birds. Rufous-bellied kookaburras are smaller than other kookaburra species<ref>{{cite book| author = John B. Dunning Jr.| title = CRC Handbook of Avian Body Masses| edition = Second| year = 2008| publisher = CRC PressI Llc| isbn = 978-1-4200-6444-5| page = 212 }}</ref> at around {{convert|143|g|oz|1|abbr=on}} as against the [[laughing kookaburra]]'s {{convert|335|g|oz|1|abbr=on}} and about {{convert|28|cm|in|1|abbr=on}}<ref name="photographic">{{cite book| author = Morten Strange| title = A Photographic Guide to the Birds of Indonesia| year = 2001| isbn = 978-0-691-11495-8| page = 186 }}</ref> as against the laughing kookaburra's {{convert|46|cm|in|1|abbr=on}}. Despite this major size difference, the rufous-bellied kookaburra has been known to form (infertile) hybrids with all other kookaburra species,<ref name="handbook">{{cite book| author = Eugene M. McCarthy| title = Handbook of Avian Hybrids of the World| date = 2006-02-16| publisher = Oxford University Press, USA| isbn = 978-0-19-518323-8| page = 118 }}</ref> though available genetic studies suggest it is clearly the most distant of the four.<ref name="handbook"/>

This kookaburra is unusual in that it occupies dense [[rainforest]]s (as opposed to the open country preferred by other kookaburras) and does not live in [[cooperative breeding]] family groups, but singly, or when breeding, in pairs. Rufous-bellied kookaburras can be found in the middle story of the tropical rainforest, where they fly out directly and swiftly from their perch to seize large insects from trees.<ref name ="photographic"/> Despite their direct flight, rufous-bellied kookaburras are capable of very sharp twists and turns around the dense trees that form their habitat. They have been known also to hunt small vertebrates, but do so less frequently than the larger woodland kookaburras, and frequently are mobbed by smaller birds when they prey on their eggs or nestlings.<ref name="kingfishers"/> Males are very aggressive in defending their territories, which average {{convert|2|to|2.5|ha|acre|1|abbr=on}} in size, and sometimes fight intruders violently.
[[File:Sauromarptis gaudichaudii 27.jpg|thumb|upright|left|Skeleton]]
Like their larger relatives, rufous-bellied kookaburras breed in termite mounds. Breeding usually takes place from May to October, though the young do not disperse fully until February, and pairs have not been known to attempt a second brood in one year.<ref name="kingfishers"/> Two white eggs are laid, though the actual incubation period is not known.

